<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In a fractional reserve banking system with a 10% reserve requirement, what is the maximum money multiplier?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">5</option>
            <option letter="b">10</option>
            <option letter="c">15</option>
            <option letter="d">20</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The money multiplier is calculated as 1/reserve ratio. With a 10% (0.10) reserve requirement, the multiplier is 1/0.10 = 10.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which of the following is NOT considered part of M1 money supply?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Currency in circulation</option>
            <option letter="b">Small-denomination time deposits</option>
            <option letter="c">Savings accounts</option>
            <option letter="d">Demand deposits</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>As of May 2020, savings accounts are included in M1. Small-denomination time deposits (like CDs) are part of M2 but not M1.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>When a bank makes a new loan, what happens to its T-account?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Assets decrease, liabilities decrease</option>
            <option letter="b">Assets increase, liabilities stay same</option>
            <option letter="c">Assets increase, liabilities increase</option>
            <option letter="d">Assets stay same, liabilities increase</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>When a bank makes a loan, it creates both an asset (the loan) and a liability (the deposit) simultaneously, increasing both sides of the T-account.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which function of money allows us to compare prices of different goods?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Medium of exchange</option>
            <option letter="b">Store of value</option>
            <option letter="c">Unit of account</option>
            <option letter="d">Standard of deferred payment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The unit of account function of money provides a common measure of value, making it possible to compare prices of different goods and services.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>If a bank has $100,000 in deposits and a 20% reserve requirement, what is its required reserve amount?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">$5,000</option>
            <option letter="b">$10,000</option>
            <option letter="c">$20,000</option>
            <option letter="d">$80,000</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Required reserves = Deposits × Reserve ratio. So $100,000 × 0.20 = $20,000 in required reserves.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
